Is it dangerous to fall asleep inside of a car with the windows up

2025-07-15T19:32:05.386605Z assistant

Yes, it can be dangerous to fall asleep in a car with the windows upespecially in warm weather or if the engine is running.

Heres a breakdown based on key conditions:

Engine Off, Windows Up (Most Common)

  • Oxygen levels: You won't suffocatethe air volume in a car is usually sufficient for several hours, especially if you're alone.
  • Risk: The greater danger is heat. Even at night, the inside of a car can get warm and cause dehydration or overheating, especially in humid places like Florida.
  • Mitigation: Crack a window slightly to allow airflow, especially if its not too cold outside.

Warm/Humid Climate (e.g. Florida)

  • Cars can act like greenhouses and trap heat.
  • Even at night, humidity + lack of airflow can cause restless sleep, headaches, dehydration, or in extreme cases, heatstroke.
  • Keep water near, and avoid bundling up too much.

Engine Running, Windows Up

  • Never sleep this way in a garage or enclosed space risk of carbon monoxide poisoning.
  • Even outdoors, a leaking exhaust system or blocked tailpipe (like from mud or tall grass) could trap CO gas.
  • Its best to turn off the engine and only run it briefly if absolutely necessary for A/C or heat.

Best Practices if You Must Sleep in the Car

  • Crack 2 windows slightly on opposite sides for cross ventilation.
  • Keep water within reach and hydrate before sleeping.
  • Use reflective shades if parked under sun or in a visible area.
  • Choose a safe, legal, and well-ventilated location.

If youre feeling weak, hot, dizzy, or short of breath after waking in the car, get out immediately and hydrate.
